<%- include('../../partials/implementer-core.md.ejs', { specificsBlock: `## Node.js TypeScript Backend Specifics

### NestJS Patterns
- Define DTOs with \`class-validator\` decorators; validate at the boundary with \`ValidationPipe\`.
- Use constructor injection for all dependencies — never property injection or manual instantiation.
- Guards, interceptors, and pipes must be injected via module providers, not instantiated inline.
- Keep controllers thin: delegate all logic to service classes, not inline in route handlers.

### Express / Fastify / Hono Patterns
- Group routes by resource in dedicated router files; register routers in a central \`app.ts\`.
- Validate and parse request bodies with Zod at the route boundary before touching business logic.
- Return typed response objects — never \`res.json(anyObject)\`.

### Testing
- Use \`jest\` + \`supertest\` for integration tests against the real HTTP layer.
- One integration test per route covering the happy path + one error case minimum.
- Unit-test service classes in isolation with mocked repositories.

### Anti-patterns to avoid
- Never use \`any\` for request/response types — define explicit interfaces.
- Never share mutable state between requests (module-level variables).
- Never swallow errors in middleware — always call \`next(err)\` or return a typed error response.
- Never hardcode secrets — use environment variables validated at startup with Zod.
- Never block the event loop with sync I/O in route handlers.` }) %>
